6. Explain the ”Three-Click Rule” and its significance in User Experience (UX) design.
The Three-Click Rule is a web design guideline which suggests that 
a user should be able to find any information on a website within three mouse clicks from the homepage.

Significance in UX Design:
	•	Improves Usability: Users can access information quickly without frustration.
	•	Reduces Cognitive Load: Minimizes effort and confusion while navigating.
	•	Enhances User Satisfaction: Faster and simpler navigation encourages users to stay on the site.

Although modern UX focuses more on ease of navigation and clarity rather than strictly counting clicks, 
the principle still emphasizes efficient and intuitive navigation.

7. ”Plan before you do.” Explain how tools like Card Sorting and Flowcharts help in planning
a website’s structure.
Effective website planning ensures that the site is organized, user-friendly, and meets goals before development begins. 
Tools like Card Sorting and Flowcharts help in this planning process:
	1.	Card Sorting:
	•	Users or designers organize topics or content into categories using cards.
	•	Helps determine a logical and intuitive structure for menus, navigation, and content grouping.
	•	Ensures the website matches user expectations.
	2.	Flowcharts:
	•	Visual diagrams that show the sequence of pages, user interactions, and navigation paths.
	•	Helps identify the workflow, decision points, and dependencies between pages.
	•	Ensures efficient information flow and reduces confusion in navigation.

Conclusion:
Using these tools prevents structural issues, reduces rework, and improves user experience, reinforcing the principle: plan before you do.


